photos.Observation Details: Initially seen catching insects over the slough on the east side of the island.  It then perched facing us relatively close for a few seconds.  It's dark charcoal gray head and chest with a contrasting white chin made us immediately think it was a Cassin's.  The head was much darker gray than is typically seen on a Western Kingbird.  The bird then flew down off the levee to a fence behind a locked gate.  John made careful field observations through his scope while I made feeble attempts at taking pictures.  While the pictures are blurry, they show the key field marks that were seen in the field.  Specifically, the dark charcoal gray head and chest contrasting with the white chin.   From John's scope views of the bird flying and spreading its tail, there were definitely no white outer tail feathers.  Despite the clear views of the tail, the pale tip that is often seen on Cassin's was not visible.  Through the scope, the color of the tail was more of a dark brown as opposed to the jet black of a Western Kingbird.

I frequently see puffed out Hutton's Vireos in the bushes near the bird bath and had assumed they were different individuals from the more normal looking Hutton's.  These pictures are all of the same bird.

photos.Observation Details: (37.8214957, -121.6414163)  The Tricoloreds would frequently sit on the fence near the cattails.  All appeared to be male, although there was 1 female that I could not identify for sure.  They were also seen feeding on the hillside beyond the fence.  They would go into the cattails and disappear.  There were a couple of Red-winged Blackbirds sharing the area as well as 4 or 5 Brewer's.  Initially thought they might be breeding in the cattails, however, when I returned on 5/2/20 to check the location again, there were no Tricolored's.   The two most likely scenarios that come to mind are: 1) the Tricoloreds were just checking the location out, but found it unsuitable, 2) they finished breeding by 5/2 and had moved out.  The landowner from nearby spoke with me.  He was very concerned about "environmentalists" messing up his land.  Nevertheless, he was pleasant/civil.

photos.Observation Details: Saw a robin-size all red bird fly across the road in front of me and down the hill.  I figured it was either a Cardinal, a Summer Tanager, or I was hallucinating from dehydration. I figured the latter was more likely.  After waiting around a bit, I spotted a male Summer Tanager sitting in a dead oak below me.  It was all red with a pale tanager-shaped bill.    The coordinates where the tanager flew across the road are: (37.8727258, -121.9175456).  It is where Green Ranch Road has a sharp bend, and there is a lot of lush, shaded vegetation and deciduous trees with some running water. Just the kind of place I would want to hang out if I were a lost Summer Tanager.
